data.current_description: Applies one or more updates to the spreadsheet. Each request is validated before being applied. If any request is not valid then the entire request will fail and nothing will be applied. Some requests have replies to give you some information about how they are applied. The replies will mirror the requests. For example, if you applied 4 updates and the 3rd one had a reply, then the response will have 2 empty replies, the actual reply, and another empty reply, in that order. Due to the collaborative nature of spreadsheets, it is not guaranteed that the spreadsheet will reflect exactly your changes after this completes, however it is guaranteed that the updates in the request will be applied together atomically. Your changes may be altered with respect to collaborator changes. If there are no collaborators, the spreadsheet should reflect your changes.

Specifying one or more data filters returns the portions of the spreadsheet that intersect ranges matched by any of the filters. By default, data within grids is not returned. You can include grid data one of 2 ways: * Specify a [field mask](https://developers.google.com/workspace/sheets/api/guides/field-masks) listing your desired fields using the `fields` URL parameter in HTTP * Set the includeGridData parameter to true. data.current_description: Applies one or more updates to the spreadsheet. Each request is validated before being applied. If any request is not valid then the entire request will fail and nothing will be applied. Some requests have replies to give you some information about how they are applied. The replies will mirror the requests. For example, if you applied 4 updates and the 3rd one had a reply, then the response will have 2 empty replies, the actual reply, and another empty reply, in that order. Due to the collaborative nature of spreadsheets, it is not guaranteed that the spreadsheet will reflect exactly your changes after this completes, however it is guaranteed that the updates in the request will be applied together atomically. Your changes may be altered with respect to collaborator changes. If there are no collaborators, the spreadsheet should reflect your changes.
data.summary_suggestion: Apply multiple updates to spreadsheet atomically
data.description_suggestion: Applies one or more updates to a spreadsheet atomically. Each update request is validated before application; if any request is invalid, the entire batch fails and no changes are applied. Accepts a BatchUpdateSpreadsheetRequest containing a list of requests (e.g., UpdateCellsRequest, AddSheetRequest, UpdateSheetPropertiesRequest). Returns a BatchUpdateSpreadsheetResponse with replies corresponding to each request in order (empty replies for requests without responses). Updates are applied atomically, though in collaborative environments, other users' concurrent changes may affect the final state. Ideal for complex multi-step spreadsheet modifications.

data.current_description: Returns the spreadsheet at the given ID. The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID. This method differs from GetSpreadsheet in that it allows selecting which subsets of spreadsheet data to return by specifying a dataFilters parameter. Multiple DataFilters can be specified. Specifying one or more data filters returns the portions of the spreadsheet that intersect ranges matched by any of the filters. By default, data within grids is not returned. You can include grid data one of 2 ways: * Specify a [field mask](https://developers.google.com/workspace/sheets/api/guides/field-masks) listing your desired fields using the `fields` URL parameter in HTTP * Set the includeGridData parameter to true. If a field mask is set, the `includeGridData` parameter is ignored For large spreadsheets, as a best practice, retrieve only the specific spreadsheet fields that you want.
data.summary_suggestion: Retrieve spreadsheet data filtered by ranges
data.description_suggestion: Retrieves spreadsheet metadata and optionally grid data for ranges matching specified data filters. Requires the spreadsheet ID and one or more DataFilters to identify target ranges. By default, returns only spreadsheet metadata (properties, sheets, named ranges). To include grid data, either set includeGridData to true or specify a field mask via the `fields` URL parameter. Multiple DataFilters can be specified; the response includes data from all matching ranges. Returns a Spreadsheet object containing the requested data. Use this method instead of GetSpreadsheet when you need to retrieve data from specific ranges only, improving performance for large spreadsheets.

data.current_description: Appends values to a spreadsheet. The input range is used to search for existing data and find a "table" within that range. See the [guide](https://developers.google.com/workspace/sheets/api/guides/values#appending_values) and [sample code](https://developers.google.com/workspace/sheets/api/samples/writing#append_values) for specific details of how tables are detected and data is appended. The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID, range, and a valueInputOption. The `valueInputOption` only controls how the input data will be added to the sheet (column-wise or row-wise), it does not influence what cell the data starts being written to.
data.summary_suggestion: Append values to next available row in table

The input range is searched to identify table boundaries, and values are appended starting with the first column of the table. Requires spreadsheet ID, range, and valueInputOption (which controls column-wise or row-wise input orientation). Returns an AppendValuesResponse containing the updated range, row count, and column count. Only cell values are modified; formatting and data validation are preserved.

data.current_description: Returns the spreadsheet at the given ID. The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID. By default, data within grids is not returned. You can include grid data in one of 2 ways: * Specify a [field mask](https://developers.google.com/workspace/sheets/api/guides/field-masks) listing your desired fields using the `fields` URL parameter in HTTP * Set the includeGridData URL parameter to true. If a field mask is set, the `includeGridData` parameter is ignored For large spreadsheets, as a best practice, retrieve only the specific spreadsheet fields that you want. To retrieve only subsets of spreadsheet data, use the ranges URL parameter. Ranges are specified using [A1 notation](https://developers.google.com/workspace/sheets/api/guides/concepts#cell). You can define a single cell (for example, `A1`) or multiple cells (for example, `A1:D5`). You can also get cells from other sheets within the same spreadsheet (for example, `Sheet2!A1:C4`) or retrieve multiple ranges at once (for example, `?ranges=A1:D5&ranges=Sheet2!A1:C4`). Limiting the range returns only the portions of the spreadsheet that intersect the requested ranges.
data.summary_suggestion: Retrieve spreadsheet metadata and optionally grid data
data.description_suggestion: Retrieves a spreadsheet's metadata and structure by spreadsheetId. By default, returns only metadata (SheetProperties, formatting, etc.) without grid cell data. To include grid data, use either the includeGridData parameter (returns all data) or the ranges parameter with A1 notation to retrieve specific cell ranges (e.g., 'A1:D5' or 'Sheet2!A1:C4'). Alternatively, use the fields parameter with a field mask to specify exact fields. Returns a Spreadsheet object containing the requested data.
